South African Corn Prices Decline, Tracking Chicago Benchmark

-- B y   C a r l i   L o u r e n s
-- 
2011-03-10T11:29:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-10/south-african-corn-prices-decline-tracking-chicago-benchmark.html
Corn prices retreated in  South
Africa , the largest producer of the grain in the continent, as
Chicago prices fell for a fifth day.  White corn for July delivery, the most active contract on
the South African Futures Exchange, declined 40 rand, or 2.4
percent, to 1,620 rand ($236) a metric ton at the 12 p.m. close
of trade in Johannesburg. Meal made from the grain is the
countryâ€™s staple food.  Corn futures for May delivery slid 3 cents, or 0.4 percent,
to $6.98 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade in electronic
trading today, after four straight days of losses.  In South Africa, yellow corn for July delivery fell 38
rand, or 2.2 percent, to 1,656 rand a ton. The country mainly
uses the grain as  animal feed .  Wheat for May delivery fell 40 rand, or 1.3 percent, to
3,050 rand a ton.  Gains or losses for the most active contracts of three
additional crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
